Part I - Used Cars Data¶

by Adeoje Olabisi¶

Introduction¶

The dataset is madeup of 7906 rows and 18 columns in general. Based on various market surveys, the consulting firm has gathered a large dataset of different types of used cars across the market. The dataset is madeup of different information about used cars gotten from kaggle.. The description of data can be gotten from here.

Data Dictionary:

  • Sales_ID (Sales ID)
  • name (Name of the used car)
  • year (Year of the car purchase)
  • selling_price (Current selling price for used car)
  • km_driven (Total km driven)
  • Region (Region where it is used)
  • State or Province (State or Province where it is used)
  • City (City where it is used)
  • fuel (Fuel type)
  • seller_type (Who is selling the car)
  • transmission (Transmission type of the car)
  • transmission (Transmission type of the car)
  • owner (Owner type)
  • mileage (Mileage of the car)
  • engine (engine power)
  • max_power (max power)
  • seats (Number of seats)
  • sold (used car sold or not)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset is madeup of 7906 records with 18 variables used to describe each records. Where selling_price, km_driven, mileage, max_power, seat and engine are the main numeric variables. There are no ordinal variables in the dataset.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

My main focus is to see the main features that affect the selling price of the used cars.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

Some of the features that I presume will dictate the prices of cars are mileage, engine, seats, seller_type, fuel type and the transmission type.

In [10]:
# Functions for various plots
def Hist_bin(data, x, xlabel, ylabel, title, bins):
    import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
    plt.hist(data=data, x=x, bins=bins)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.title(title, loc='center');
    
def Hist(data, x, xlabel, ylabel, title):
    import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
    plt.hist(data=data, x=x)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.title(title, loc='center');
    
def Scatter(data, x, y, xlabel, ylabel):
    import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
    plt.scatter(data=data, x=x, y=y, alpha=0.2)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel);
    
def violin(data, x, y, title):
    import seaborn as sb
    a = sb.violinplot(data=data, x=x, y=y, inner=None, color=def_color);
    plt.title(title);
    
def Box(data, x, y, title):
    import seaborn as sb
    a = sb.boxplot(data=data, x=x, y=y, color=def_color);
    plt.title(title);

def Facet(data, col, colwrap, map_func, var1, var2):
    a = sb.FacetGrid(data=data, col=col, col_wrap=colwrap, height=4)
    a.map(map_func, var1, var2)
    a.set_titles('{col_name}');

In [12]:
# Transformed distribution of selling price of used cars
bin=np.arange(30000, 10000000, 100000)
plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
Hist_bin(df, 'selling_price', 'Selling Price ($)', 'Count', 'Transformed Distribution of Selling Price', bins=bin)
plt.xscale('log')
plt.xticks([30000,100000,300000,1000000,3000000,10000000], ['30K','100K','300K','1M','3M','10M']);
Observation¶

In a bit to look at the distribution of selling price across the data set, the histogram shows that cars whose selling price is between \$30,000 and \\$1,000,000 are much in the dataset. But in order to dive deeper into the dataset, log transformation was carried out on the price axis, this later shows that the price distribution is a unimodal distribution in which the modal price is in between \$300,000 and \\$400,000. After \$1,000,000, it was oberved that the price is rising and falling in the counts.

Question¶

Did fuel type has anything to do with the mileage of cars in the dataset?

In [33]:
# Relationship between fuel types and mileage of cars
sum = df.groupby('fuel').sum()
total_mileage=df.mileage.sum()
sum['mileage_prop'] = sum.mileage/total_mileage
plt.figure(figsize=(12,5))
plt.subplot(1,2,1)
ax = sb.barplot(data=df, x='fuel', y='mileage', ci=0, color=def_color)
ax.set_title('Average Mileage of Fuel Types');
plt.subplot(1,2,2)
ax = sb.barplot(data=sum, x=sum.index, y='mileage_prop', ci=0, color=def_color)
ax.set_title('Mileage Proportion of Fuel Types');
Observation¶

The average mileage (mpg) of cars with various fuel types shows that cars using CNG are good for fuel economy followed by the one using diesel. Mileage proportion of fuel types shows that cars using diesel has the largest proportion of the total mileage in the dataset, recall that diesel has the largest distribution of fuel types in the dataset, hence, taking the largest proportion of mileage.

Observation¶

The charts above shows the trends of price of sold cars over years across regions. The faceting of the region help us to see that some regions do not have sales in some years; like the Southern region which has no sales until 2001 and has no sale in 2003. The faceting also show further that the sales is peak in the year 2019 across the regions as we have it in the general sales. It also shows that the South has the highest sale in 2019 which happens to be outrageous compared to that of other regions.

Conclusions¶

I've seen that the two major variables that affect the selling price of cars in the dataset are max_power and km_driven. I also saw the time trends of sales across the regions, where it was observed that some of the regions do not have sale in some years.

In a bit to explore the data, I carried out univariate visualization which allow me to see into the distribution of various variables in the dataset across its levels. I also carried out bivariate visualization which shows the relationship between variables while multivariate visualization is used to show the effect of some variables on the relationships in bivariate visualization. The exploration has help to see the strong correlation between max_power and engine variables.
